{"questionId":"34907403","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Helen and Jane both commence new jobs each starting on an annual salary of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>70</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>000</mn></math>. At&nbsp;the start of each new year, Helen receives an annual salary increase of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>2400</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> represent Helen’s annual salary at the start of her <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>th year of employment.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2400</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>67</mn><mo> </mo><mn>600</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p style=\"color:#999;font-size:90%;font-style:italic;\">* This sample question was produced by experienced DP mathematics senior examiners to aid teachers in preparing for external assessment in the new MAA course. There may be minor differences in formatting compared to formal exam papers.</p>\n<p>uses&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>d</mi></math>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>70</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2400</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>(M1)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>70</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2400</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>A1</strong></p>\n<p>so&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2400</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>67</mn><mo> </mo><mn>600</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>AG</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2</strong><strong>&nbsp;marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"34907403","referenceCode":"EXN.2.SL.TZ0.7a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that Hn=2400n+67 600.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.2—Arithmetic sequences and series","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.3—Geometric sequences and series","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.4—Financial apps – compound int, annual depreciation"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}